    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "cf619804_e1da1cab",
        "filename": "handler/win/loader_lock_dll.cc",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 25,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-10-04T15:40:45Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I gave some thought to this not for the logging but for the use of swscanf(). I originally wrote something with StrToInt64Ex() that brought in a dependency on shlwapi just to avoid the CRT. But it was very casty and needed something slightly different for 32-bit, so I didn’t really like it. I convinced myself that the only way the CRT might be a bad idea was if it was a CRT DLL delay-loaded by loader_lock_dll.dll and not otherwise loaded by hanging_program.exe, but even then, the loader lock is “recursive” so it probably wouldn’t be a problem. And it seemed pretty unlikely for those two modules to have different CRT configurations since they both just exist in support of each other for this test, so I thought that it wasn’t worth worrying about.\n\nIf that’s safe, then I don’t see a reason that the formatted output stuff wouldn’t be. I could cool it with some of the formatting stuff, but I didn’t want to give up the line number, and it’s much more of a pain to convert that to a string without something from the printf family.",
      "parentUuid": "02c47582_3e37c9ca",
